==English==
===Etymology===
adaptation of medieval Latin ''analyticus,'' from Greek άνάλυτικ analytic, from άνάυτοσ, dissolved, dissolvable, from άνάλύειν
===Adjective===
#of or relating to analysis or analytics; ''especially:'' separating or breaking up a whole or a compound into its component parts or constituent elements "an ''analytic'' experiment", "''analytic'' reasoning"
#skilled in or using analysis "a keenly ''analytic'' man"
#''logic:'' of or relating to a truth, a proposition, or a statement that is true in all possible worlds, that is true independently of any facts by reference to meanings alone, or that is logically true or definitionally reducible to logical truth
#characterized by analysis rather than inflection "English is an ''analytic'' language" --contrasted with [[synthetic]]
#[[psychoanalytic|PSYCHOANALYTIC]]
#treated by the methods or represented by the symbolism of algebra or calculus <analytic statics> -- distinguished from [[graphic]]
#''of a function of a real variable:'' capable of being expanded in a [[wikipedia:Taylor's series|Taylor's series]] in powers of ''x - h'' in some neighborhood of the point ''h''
#of a function of a [[wikipedia:complex variable|complex variable]]: differentiable at every point in some neighborhood of a given point or points
===Noun===
#something that is analytic
#'''a.''' that part of logic which treats of analysis. '''b.''' ''obsolete:'' the algebraical branches of [[wikipedia:pure mathematics|pure mathematics]]; the application of algebra to geometry.
